he 1960s and 1970s, assess the convergence of film-industry developments and momentous social and political changes that created a new type of commercial film that reflected those revolutionary influences in American life. Even as New Hollywood first took shape, film industry insiders and commentators alike realized its significance. At the time, Pauline Kael compared the New Hollywood to the "tangled, bitter flowering of American letters in the 1850s" and David Thomson dubbed the era "the decade when movies mattered." Thomson's words provide the impetus for this volume in which a cohort of seasoned film critics and scholars who came of age watching the movies of this era reflect upon and reconsider this golden age in American filmmaking.Contributors: Molly Haskell, Heather Hendershot, J. Hoberman, George Kouvaros, Phillip Lopate, Robert Pippin, David Sterritt, David Thomson  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aCultural Studies. 4aFilm. 4aU.S. History. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  afilm industry, commercial film, american filmmaking, American life, New Hollywood.1 aHaskell, Molly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHendershot, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoberman, J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirshner, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKirshner, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKouvaros, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLe